text:
üñ§photo by @amivitale.  @time magazine named the #metoo movement as the person of the year, a movement that has brought so many women forward to tell their stories in order to change the systematic #gender imbalances and violence against women across the world. this movement reveals how much further we have to go in eradicating them and also that we are making great strides in getting there. 
it's moments like these that i am reminded how proud i am to be a part of @rippleeffectimages, helping #empower women and girls world wide through education opportunities. if we can create a world with a truly equal playing field, we will have the power to change it.

this photo was taken during a #fulani baby naming ceremony and the girls put on lipstick for the special occasion. there were a lot of beautiful healthy fat babies there, despite this being a very dry and remote part of #benin. the women told me it was because of a solar irrigated garden and how much it helped changed their lives.

day 15: rosa parks
no we are not getting lazy; we know you all know rosa parks. but did you know that @taranajaneen and the #metoo movement today is in fact part of a long history of activists fighting sexual harassment. and one of the activists more commonly associated with another movement was a key figure in early attempts to rectify sexual injustice: rosa parks. read more: https://www.history.com/news/before-the-bus-rosa-parks-was-a-sexual-assault-investigator

every day for #blackhistorymonth, we are going to share some knowledge about black americans that we never got in school. we challenge all our followers to amplify! repost, tag us and make sure to include #showup.

i reclaim the power i was told i didn't have.

if you want to see this piece in person, it is in downtown culver city, on robertson next to the entrance of the 10

i'll also be telling the story more in depth over the next few posts so stay tuned.

text:
aviation: eternity (10/10) by nicholas jones, 14 december 2018. -

when i lay down alone at night - i toss and turn to sleep,
because when i‚Äôm laying here in this bed without you - i feel empty,
the room will spin - turn dark and cold,
because to have you inside and not to hold,
feels like one-hundred lifetimes spent yearning for truth,
a trust i once had but lost when i lost you,

you are not alone in this world - that‚Äôs what they say,
we all deal with things in our own way,
and in our own time - but when will the time come for me,
to fly again the way that i used to fly when i loved her,
but on my own - because it‚Äôs harder for me to love myself,
than it is for me to love anybody else - it seems,

aviation is just a dream if you don‚Äôt  have the wings,
to lift you off the ground and propel you forward into motion,
and i know i can never learn to navigate the oceans,
if i‚Äôm sitting on the shore watching life pass me by,
so i guess i‚Äôll keep trying even when it hurts,

we‚Äôd be so good - and we‚Äôd be even greater together,
and in my dreams - you‚Äôll always be mine,
and i‚Äôll know exactly where i need to go to find you,
because life and death may part us now,
but i feel like you can still hear me - someway - somehow,

and i can hold onto each and every one of these memories for an eternity,
because when you made yourself a part of me,
i knew that part of you would never leave,
and though my soul may sail to secret seas,
i will always have you inside of me - for an eternity,
two birds one feather fly together - and the rest is history. -

text:
.
happy #fortyfive4friday !
.
lesley gore - you don‚Äôt own me / run bobby, run (1963)
.
‚Äúyou don't own me" was one of the very first songs in which a woman demands her independence from a man.  gore was just 17 when she recorded this hit song and it was a big departure in tone from her last hit ‚Äúit‚Äôs my party‚Äù. along with betty friedan's book the feminine mystique (which was published shortly before this song's release), the single is considered one of a many works of art that helped begin the women's liberation movement. the song was written by john madara and david white and put in front of gore through her producer, quincy jones. putting aside its significance, it‚Äôs just a great song due to gore‚Äôs defiant vocals and playful musical composition. please excuse my ignorance, i don‚Äôt know what‚Äôs it‚Äôs called but the change in sound between the verse and the refrain of this song is stellar. maybe major to minor chord change?
.
i chose this song today as the recent nyt article on ryan adams has been on my mind. i agree with the label‚Äôs decision to pull his upcoming album but i‚Äôm selfishly bummed out because i love his music. i guess we can add three more albums (there were 2 more promised for this year) to his already long list of unreleased material. on the plus side, all day long refunds for the various variant pressings have been coming through. now how should i spend those funds? they were earmarked for vinyl so i can‚Äôt spend it on anything else. maybe i‚Äôll buy some more bridgers and phair.
. üá∫üá∏‚Äô63
.

text:
two new ones added to the collection.

first one is a survivor symbol. a white rose to represent rebirth with a flame to represent strength, and growth. originally designed for sexual assault survivors during the #metoo movement, who i stand behind 100%, but for me i identify it as a representation of the many battles i have survived in life, such as my mental health issues... which brings me to my other new tat. also on my wrist, (but on the opposite arm) is a symbol to honor mental health awareness, a semi-colon inside of an infinity symbol. it states that my story will never be over. mental health is a big issue in today‚Äôs society and should not be taken lightly. if you or someone you know is battling with depression, anxiety, etc., please do not hesitate to reach out. we are in this together, and with love and kindness we can continue to grow together. if you are reading this and are battling with mental health issues, just know that i love you and am here for you, with open arms. üíï

text:
i love this. .
.
there is so much brilliance in every human; and it used to be that children universally had it effortlessly. a healthy culture recognizes that truth and manages to keep it intact, so that the majority of adults are also brilliant.‚Ä®.
.‚Ä®contemporary western culture (and most others worldwide) don‚Äôt do that any more. they manage to beat brilliance out of children at an early age via unhealthy social norms, well meaning but ignorant parenting techniques, misguided standards in government funded public education, and systemically induced stress. swipe for a couple of gabor mat√© talks discussing some of these key points.‚Ä®.
.‚Ä®currently, there are even other issues: a child can be (read: is always, but the degree varies) physiologically poisoned in utero and certainly after birth, to the point that their access to their innate brilliance is quashed before they even get to the point of expressing it‚Äîbefore adults have an opportunity to ignore them, to not cultivate that brilliance, and to shove that spark deeply into submission. .
.
this tiger poem speaks to the deep wildness within us (commonly associated with the feminine or yin; the dark, uncomfortable, and disregarded part of everyone), that has to rise sometimes to break through the bounds of artificial limitations on our full and healthy expression. and even though it‚Äôs disruptive, when it‚Äôs the right thing, it‚Äôs the right thing. .
.

text:
‚Ä¢panic attacks‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢panic attacks are the pits. period. sometimes i‚Äôll have horrific nightmares or triggers that make me feel as though i‚Äôm having a heart attack. before experiencing severe trauma, i was fortunate in the sense that i had never known what it was like to have one of these ‚Äúattacks‚Äù. i have found the following tips helpful in helping calm myself during a panic attack:
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢grounding: using all 5 of my senses to bring me into the present. this helps me to know that the trauma isn‚Äôt happening right now, and that it happened in the past.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢deep breaths: this helps to slow my heart rate and helps to slow my breathing.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢imagery: imagining being in a safe place. i have a specific setting in my head that feels safe to me. imagining detail in this place is especially helpful. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢muscle relaxation: tensing and then relaxing each muscle group is calming to me.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢calling a family member who knows me well, and who knows how my ptsd affects me.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢forcing my dogs to let me bear-hug them (i find this technique to be extremely helpful).
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢therapy: my psychologist has heard it all, and she knows my biggest triggers. she knows her stuff, and she helps me to understand why i‚Äôm experiencing panic attacks and she helps remind me of interventions that have worked for me
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢exercise: i especially hate how panic attacks (for me at least) mimic heart attack symptoms. regular exercise encourages me to have a healthy heart, which in the moment of an attack, reminds me that i‚Äôm likely not having a heart attack and it‚Äôs just the ptsd roaring it‚Äôs ugly head. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢i know that there are many other interventions that are supposed to be helpful during panic attacks, but these have been the most helpful for me. i hope some of you will find these helpful too!

#yourenotalone #metoo #mentalhealthawareness #stigma

text: it's been a nice day, so far, all around. lately i've been thinking about life per usual. feeling good about moving here, some days more difficult than others. excited about some projects to stay busy. moving forward is a daily jam, sometimes during the difficult moments breathe is all you have to stay moving. progression always has it's temporary highs and lows, i suppose. yet to consider, for the different is not dangerous, it's part of humanity to question the unknown, although destroying the unknown does no good. different can be dangerous, as can anyone and anything. known or not. running from what's comfortable, is what all our ancestors did at one point to fulfill their ultimate curiosities. has created throughout humanity some of the most wonderful customs and architecture, hobbies, studies, and lifestyles to experience. it can be a great world at the same time as addressing the areas to complete definitive progress. there's a lot to accomplish, in attempt to leave the world in liveable shape for the next generations. global awareness obviously has it's high and low points, although, i'm happy to know things about other countries. it's cool they're working on curing cancer. theres a cancer stopping tree we could plant more of though. it has brought an enormous amount of awareness to civil rights matters. i do not stand for any of the actions of cruelty performed by the sherbert. it does affect us. as well, there are 49 dictators across the globe, climate change is a priority, they aren't. maybe global awareness can help with that, or the removal of them, and the plastic, as we rebalance into a reformed justice system of sorts.  its good to refocus and maintain, for me personally right now, and its cool to see some positive influence in the community, thats important for representation, overall morale, and the environment itself.  #freepress #metoo #blacklivesmatter #waterprotectors

text: set in the mid-'70s in chautauqua, new york, we were the mulvaneys showed me the importance of the #metoo movement once again. it's a true horror story that most victims of sexual abuse aren't given the support they needed. it is painful to live day by day in this world knowing that people are being harassed and abused but it is much worse that there are people out there who chose to turn their backs on them. it is in moment like this that i want to shout for everyone to hear the importance of #feminism in this world. #believewomen (if you're still reading up to this point, thank you and please stand up for the victims. be sensitive. don't be afraid to speak up. we will all get thru this one closed fist at a time, so your support matters.)

text:
***full poem in caption*** unfold these edges
i am not a page
you want to come back to

broken by the hands
of men before you
my pieces do not make a whole
too many went missing

i want to show you
what it is to burn
from the inside out
eventually i went numb
nothing but dead skin

a stranger in my head
familiar but foreign
says it‚Äôs okay to bleed
i don‚Äôt want to know her

this baggage gets heavy
i draw maps of my body
the places you cannot touch
the parts that scream too loud
the pieces where love cannot enter

i sleep with lights on
hearts break in the dark -jhm

text:
an ode to liberated women - the sketches

liberation is different for every woman and it is only upto her what she defines as liberation in her journey. here we show a journey that starts from a past rooted in pain: a kind of pain that gives one depth, and moves towards healing: here there are breaths to be taken and a lesson to be recalled. lesson that height is just as important as depth to create balance and height cannot be reached without tending to the wounds that the depth brought with it. finally, the ladder to liberation: giving your emotions the worth they deserve, growing out of the societal expectations, choosing to not let yourself be defined by anyone or anything else other than yourself, and eventually rising above own self image as well to open your inner eyes to see how limitless you are. we chose a girl to reflect this journey of rising above because we believe it starts with her. she represents & educates the family, leads the community to health, and will eventually walk the world towards healing with her sensitivity as her strength and vulnerability as her armor.

#thesketches #anodetoliberatedwomen #metoo

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subve elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

text:
there's safety in the sister circle....
.
.
what is it about women gathering together that is so powerful? is it the shared experiences, empathy and understanding? is it the 'knowing'...something only a woman can get? is it the discussion of ideas, learning new things, empowering one another and facing tough challenges together? or just space to be silent, laugh , cry...be?
.
.
maybe it's all of these and more!
.
.
with the world in grips over politics, economics, #metoo and more it can be overwhelming trying to take everything in and maintain your sense of self, calm and balance. .
.
and with our womanhood being attacked left right and centre - by women just as well as men - it can be hard to know where to turn for support, community and just a girl gang to connect with, it can be hard to connect in person as our lives seem to be moving more and more online, however, we can choose where we spend our online time.
.
.
so with that said...
.
.
there's now an online sister circle!!
.
.
join in to be part of the conversation, share your news and stories, books and podcasts, hints and tips, dilemmas and solutions and more! this is a private group mostly formed of women who have been to one of my workshops and want to continue exploring womb steaming, womanhood and reclaiming the feminine.

even though it's online, it's still a safe space with everyone needing to adhere to the rules of the group. we're here to rediscover, reclaim and redefine....are you?
.
.
click/copy this link here to join - https://www.facebook.com/groups/mamalunacircle/
.
.
#sistercircle #onlinesistercircle #globalsistercircle #womenscircle #share #gathertogether #safety

text:
#flashback: #dutchcookiejar #2015 #medgrow. ever sit around and start thinkin too much? like , "ey, i wonder if dutch cookie jar likes me.." or "i wonder what dutch cookie jar was doing before #doubledutchfarms?"...jus  goin'  #heavyinthestreets. #metoo. i had her so dialed in that people hated me. especially cuz they were addicted to it. #mybad. this was  my final run before her move to #doubledutch. the tops would get serious af indoors for me. especially with the #minimalfeeding style i was  pursuing, i was continuously pushing the limit on yield. the less i fed, the bigger my buds got. these were fed 2 tbs of bat gauno per gallon of aerated water, once, in veg, and 2 tbs molasses per gallon in flower, every other watering. and nothing else. this group is under #1000watts of metal halide. i kno everyone swears by hps in flower, but everyone is wrong. to  be honest, i have not one use for hps. the shot above kinda proves it.  i need the extra ultraviolet of a mh to pack on that resin. hps just gives me hella pistols and looser, airy buds.  indoors where too much stretch in flower can fuck you, mh greatly reduces the stretch.  this cutt is a real shapeshifter depending on conditions. i have a hunch she doesn't really like the extra heat in the glasshouse, cuz there, she does better early spring and late fall. in the warm season her calyxes never seem to swell. they stay small and stack into denser, compact nugs. which might sound okay but if  the calyxes never swell they don't seem to open up thier full flavor and aroma. but indoors, i can keep a growroom straight at 68¬∞ (#donthate). and actually  the calyxes swell quit a bit if kept below 80¬∞. much rounder bud format,  with little to no "horning-up" or "fox-tail"-like growth. and timed for cooler weather at the beginning and end of the year in the glasshouse, when the sun is still delivering some quality light, she puts out some prime flower.
.

#flashback: #dutchcookiejar #2015 #medgrow. ever sit around and start thinkin too much? like , "ey, i wonder if dutch cookie jar likes me.." or "i wonder what dutch cookie jar was doing before #doubledutchfarms?"...jus  goin'  #heavyinthestreets. #metoo. i had her so dialed in that people hated me. especially cuz they were addicted to it. #mybad. this was  my final run before her move to #doubledutch. the tops would get serious af indoors for me. especially with the #minimalfeeding style i was  pursuing, i was continuously pushing the limit on yield. the less i fed, the bigger my buds got. these were fed 2 tbs of bat gauno per gallon of aerated water, once, in veg, and 2 tbs molasses per gallon in flower, every other watering. and nothing else. this group is under #1000watts of metal halide. i kno everyone swears by hps in flower, but everyone is wrong. to  be honest, i have not one use for hps. the shot above kinda proves it.  i need the extra ultraviolet of a mh to pack on that resin. hps just gives me hella pistols and looser, airy buds.  indoors where too much stretch in flower can fuck you, mh greatly reduces the stretch.  this cutt is a real shapeshifter depending on conditions. i have a hunch she does not really like the extra heat in the glasshouse, cuz there, she does better early spring and late fall. in the warm season her calyxes never seem to swell. they stay small and stack into denser, compact nugs. which might sound okay but if  the calyxes never swell they do not seem to open up thier full flavor and aroma. but indoors, i can keep a growroom straight at 68¬∞ (#do nothate). and actually  the calyxes swell quit a bit if kept below 80¬∞. much rounder bud format,  with little to no "horning-up" or "fox-tail"-like growth. and timed for cooler weather at the beginning and end of the year in the glasshouse, when the sun is still delivering some quality light, she puts out some prime flower.
.

the problem with kaepernick kneeling to the national anthem, is that he is black. perhaps if it a white nfl player would kneel for the black lives matter before a game, he would be heard and that makes me sick. 
perhaps if a bunch of white men spoke on the behalf of women on the #metoo movement, the president of the united states wouldn‚Äôt call her a lier. i know because i have been there, i fought with a guy because he was saying some women present themselves in a certain way, asking to get raped.. but he apologized to me after his best friend (a man) disagreed with him as well. 
the problem when you speak on someone‚Äôs behalf, is that everyone is left voiceless.

text:
trigger warning: rape & fgm -
i overheard two men talking some time ago: 
person a: would you be able to write something as a tribute to the women in our society and how their freedom and liberation is inspiring for us all?
person b: hmmm..freedom and liberation of women to what extent? where are we drawing the line? 
i wasn't shocked but still furious to see the kind of privileged mindset even the men in our literary circles live with. 
when you remind them of their privilege, they get so mad. something you have. something other people don't have. it's something you can use to amplify the marginalized's voice.
in this videos context;
i can't believe how few number of people know about fgm and the fact that this cruel practice still continues in our society and many communities in it. please talk more about it. so many women have opened up about what they've had to face in their childhood because their parents were conditioned by their religious representatives. do we even know the exact amount of girls who get raped in our country? do we have our women standing with our women yet? have we even clearly defined what rape means? how many more child abuse, marital rape, sexual harassment and assault cases will it take for our country to declare a state of emergency? #anodetowomen #metoo #ibelieveher #lahootimelo2019

our work seeks to raise public awareness, to allow community leaders to connect with the victims of sexual violence to understand their suffering first hand and to create public art as a permanent reminder of the plight of the lai dai han.

"criminal minds" star a.j. cook is suing ex-manager david guillod for failing to disclose he had multiple allegations of sexual misconduct against him.¬†(photo11: screen grab, cbs)"criminal minds" star a.j. cook is taking her former manager to task, suing him for failing to tell her and other female clients about sexual misconduct allegations against him.cook says in her lawsuit that¬†david guillod committed fraud¬†when he didn't¬†tell his clients¬†about the accusations made against him by other women.guillod's attorney, thomas ferlauto, dismissed her complaint,¬†calling it a¬†"frivolous lawsuit" in a statement sent to usa today. ferlauto added the suit cynically attempts to "piggyback" on the #metoo movement in order to avoid paying commissions she owes.but cook's attorney is returning fire."no one wants to have their good name or career tethered to someone that is accused of multiple sexual assaults," michael j. saltz¬†told usa today friday. "that is why everyone had separated themselves from harvey weinstein, bill cosby, kevin spacey, and the like prior to any charges being filed."the difference here is that mr. guillod and primary wave (the talent agency where he previously served as ceo) had a legal duty to disclose potentially harmful information about themselves to their clients so that their clients could‚Ä¶

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
america‚Äôs first billionaire president is riding into the white house with populist support ‚Äî and he‚Äôs bringing some billionaire friends with him. one of them is distressed-asset investor wilbur ross, who is trump‚Äôs pick for commerce secretary. the two have a history that spans more than 25 years.

trump made a bold bet on atlantic city when he opened a third casino there ‚Äî the colossal taj mahal ‚Äî in april 1990. even riskier: he financed the project with $675 million in junk bonds at a 14% interest rate. within months trump was struggling to make the massive bond payments as atlantic city floundered.

in stepped ross, then head of rothschild inc‚Äôs bankruptcy advising team, to represent bondholders, who were pondering forcing the casino into involuntary bankruptcy and ousting trump. ross reportedly saw crowds pressed against trump‚Äôs limo windows to get a peek at the mogul, and realized the value of trump‚Äôs celebrity.

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

to be a real queen in life is to stand firmly in the good things we believe in. i stand firmly in the belief that we need an overall safer environment against sexual harassment in the streets, workplaces, educational places, online world, etc.

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
america‚Äôs first billionaire president is riding into the white house with populist support ‚Äî and he‚Äôs bringing some billionaire friends with him. one of them is distressed-asset investor wilbur ross, who is trump‚Äôs pick for commerce secretary. the two have a history that spans more than 25 years.

trump made a bold bet on atlantic city when he opened a third casino there ‚Äî the colossal taj mahal ‚Äî in april 1990. even riskier: he financed the project with $675 million in junk bonds at a 14% interest rate. within months trump was struggling to make the massive bond payments as atlantic city floundered.

in stepped ross, then head of rothschild inc‚Äôs bankruptcy advising team, to represent bondholders, who were pondering forcing the casino into involuntary bankruptcy and ousting trump. ross reportedly saw crowds pressed against trump‚Äôs limo windows to get a peek at the mogul, and realized the value of trump‚Äôs celebrity.

text:
christopher wylie, who worked with a cambridge university academic to obtain the data, told the observer: ‚Äúwe exploited facebook to harvest millions of people‚Äôs profiles. and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.‚Äù documents seen by the observer, and confirmed by a facebook statement, show that by late 2015 the company had found out that information had been harvested on an unprecedented scale. however, at the time it failed to alert users and took only limited steps to recover and secure the private information of more than 50 million individuals.

the data was collected through an app called thisisyourdigitallife, built by academic aleksandr kogan, separately from his work at cambridge university. through his company global science research (gsr), in collaboration with cambridge analytica, hundreds of thousands of users were paid to take a personality test and agreed to have their data collected for academic use.

however, the app also collected the information of the test-takers‚Äô facebook friends, leading to the accumulation of a data pool tens of millions-strong. facebook‚Äôs ‚Äúplatform policy‚Äù allowed only collection of friends‚Äô data to improve user experience in the app and barred it being sold on or used for advertising. the discovery of the unprecedented data harvesting, and the use to which it was put, raises urgent new questions about facebook‚Äôs role in targeting voters in the us presidential election. it comes only weeks after indictments of 13 russians by the special counsel robert mueller which stated they had used the platform to perpetrate ‚Äúinformation warfare‚Äù against the us.

carole cadwalladr & emma graham-harrison
the guardian

text:
on april 16, 2017, in the village of shambhupura in banswara, rajasthan, india, kachru, 21, and monica, 19, got married and were cousins but there family, was not fine with it. the couple were paraded naked, beaten, and sexually assaulted by the whole village of shambhupura and family members including their fathers, brothers and, uncles. the accused have been booked for rioting,¬†wrongful restraint and confinement, wrongly causing hurt, attempted murder, and sexual harassment.
-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.
according to the police, on thursday, varaseng resident varanseng resident lord ratna maida, twenty-four-year-old padla resident shankar son lalji, kundelia resident forgotten wife dhulia, resident of shambhupura, gutu son shyama, subhash son hiraji, kangi son kalu, dilip son chetan, ramatu wife kalu and bhusli wife bheema was arrested¬†earlier, nine people including the father of the girl were arrested on wednesday."

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
according to the times, cambridge analytica bought the data from aleksandr kogan, a russian-american academic. kogan, who told facebook he was conducting academic research, built a facebook personality quiz app called "thisisyourdigitalife." when users downloaded the app, it scraped all of their available facebook data, including their friends, their likes and where they lived.

more than a quarter-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer". in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytica until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, supporting him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

.

.

#repost @ash_weekly „Éª„Éª„Éª
this new song by @sketchesartofficial has been on repeat since yesterday. the video is so well thought of, comes with a beautiful message of women liberation. liberation can be in many forms from being free of the societal pressures to getting out of a toxic relationship. every woman experiences liberation in one thing or the other. the end result has to be that feeling of freedom that you can feel from within. no shackles holding you up! and this is precisely what this video captures. the young girl in the video effortlessly conveys the message through, all applause to the conceptual team and the directors. location of the shoot is in sync as well. 
then come the powerful vocals by @saifsamejo you must have heard those in daastaan-e-moomal rano cs rendition. here, the vocals in perfect sync with the music, give you an altogether a different meaning to the lyrics. that sense of liberation and you are reunited with the feeling of love at the kak palace ‚ù§
i'm an avid advocate of creativity and talent and this one deserves all this and more.

halo halo kak tarrain 
jithay gharjay neenh
 na ka raat na deenh sabh ka pasay pireen khay. (let‚Äôs go to kak (the palace) the place where the story of our love is taking shape there are no nights or days anymore the place where all will be united with their beloved forever)
 halo halo kak tarrain
 jitay neenh pachaar 
kanhae ka bhi tanwaar sab ka passe pirin khay. (let‚Äôs go to kak (the palace) where love blossoms and there‚Äôs no other conversation but, of love where one is united with one‚Äôs beloved )
halo halo kak tarrain 
jith neenh uchal
 na ka jhaal na pal, sab ka passay pireen akhay. (let‚Äôs go to kak (the palace) where love flows where no one is prevented, all can be united with the beloved)

text:
***full poem below*** i have spent years
gathering my armor
building a fortress
into my skin
keeping others out
keeping me in

if i am a mountain
you are the only climber
you see beauty at the bottom
you see me at the top

hardened outside
but inside i am reaching
desperate for you to unravel me
every part of me wants
to feel your love

i took the stars
from my throat
threw them to the sky
i need you to see me
in the dark -jhm

text:
(had to change pitch of the song due to copy right) first of all i would like to say thank you to all the mixers that shared their story,it‚Äôs a step towards change. @leighsderriere , @french.muffin , @ariellaloveslm , @shadeleigh @leighadesrose @treasure.kelly & @tiadee.04 it‚Äôs 2019 yet it still feels like 1800 sometimes, women living in a man dominated society...however,we are the change we want to see,let‚Äôs get our voices heard & in action. i am sick of hearing little girls being raised with the mindset that they can‚Äôt wear something‚Äútoo revealing‚Äùbecause of men,them being told ‚Äúdon‚Äôt eat like that!‚Äù‚Äúeat like a lady‚Äù, or telling women what they should do or shouldn‚Äôt do, telling them what‚Äôs best for them. no thank you. i think we can do that for ourselves. i want to be able to feel safe walking the streets or even going to the school bathroom without thinking twice about it. i want to live in a world where my words,my voice & my ‚Äúno‚Äù matters. a world where nobody should be afraid to say the words #metoo is that too much to ask? i am not trying to victimise women, we are not looking for pity,we are looking for equality. a world where i get to be a boss,as well,where my dreams aren‚Äôt ‚Äútoo big‚Äùfor a girl & a world where i can speak without being shushed or needing to shout to be heard. i made this video to say that equality is not yet achieved,until a woman gets to decide for herself if she wants to keep a baby,until girls aren‚Äôt seen as objects and until a girl isn‚Äôt blamed for being raped because of her clothing,until then it‚Äôs not an equal world. equality is not about taking power from men it‚Äôs about also giving power to women, a world where if a man and a woman stood on a scale it would be even. 
i want to see girls being praised for their brains as well as their beauty. the bottom line is that we are a force when we stick together, @littlemix taught me that. we can be so damn powerful! we can‚Äôt ever give up girls, because we will always have each to fight for!this is us. we all are different,but skin colours,religions,ethnicities or sexuality will not keep us a part. we are one and we‚Äôre done feeling invisible! #littlemix #feminist
name: Equality. Love. Pride. üåà

text: after spiritual trauma, healing takes time, and often god uses helping professionals and/or support communities to do that. these people and communities are *being* healing church in our lives. god is very active in it! do not let others within the church pressure you to return to a church building or a find a new one before you are ready, before god speaks to your heart that it is time. going back at the wrong time can be retraumatizing and can leave us open to revictimization. sometimes, healing needs to take place elsewhere and that is okay. it is more important to *be* the church than go to church. #youareenough #lovepoweredlife #churchtoo #1john418

text: we talked about monitoring your child's cell phone yesterday and the importance of knowing what apps they're using and how those apps allow them to communicate with the outside world. today, let's look at features on their phone that can actually allow these predators to track your child's actual location. your camera, fb, instagram, and your messaging apps all have location services capabilities imbedded in them. this will place a stamp on new posts letting viewers know where the photo was taken or where the user is located when the post is uploaded. within the messaging app, your child can literally share their exact location with someone and that person can literally get turn by turn directions directly to your child. please go into your child's location services settings and disable this feature for all social media apps as well as disable or limit the feature for other apps as well. most apps and features give you the choice of selecting "never" or "while using the app". if there is no legitimate need for an app to know your child's location, select never. this may not seem like a big deal, but it is indeed a big deal. we don't want to give predators any help finding our children, so let's be intentional about ways we are proactively creating circles of safety for them. #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate #volunteer #activist #superbowl @pros4youth

text:
what is it about being drunk that makes meeting new girls and spending the whole night mingling in the bathroom or twerking on the dance floor so amazingly special? this was taken by a beautiful stranger i met at a tulane college party. we promised to dye our hair together this night, shout out to all the promises we‚Äôre too hungover to commit to. [bathroom pic]

being a girl is one of the most magical existences that i feel so honored to stand among my fellow womankind of all colors, creeds, identities, and intersections. we‚Äôre in this together! i need to remember that! we be intimidating because with us, we carry such an ancestral lineage of strength that i forget the power we share in our tenderness.

to all the girls who are chasing their dreams.
to all the girls who aren‚Äôt allowed to.
to all the girls, comrades or capitalists.
to all the girls whose sig. other i want, 
to all the girls wearing too many or too few clothes in all climates and cultures.
to my perfectionists and all the girls who just can‚Äôt get it right, but believe they will this time. you will! 
have faith, if in nothing else, in yourself.
that makes 2 of us who know u can do it!

being a girl is one of the most magical existences that i feel so honored to stand among my fellow womankind of all colors, creeds, identities, and intersections. we‚Äôre in this together! i need to remember that! we be intimidating because with us, we carry such an ancestral lineage of strength that i forget the power we share in our tenderness.

to all the girls who are chasing their dreams.

text:
workplace romance in the #metoo era
#
with valentine‚Äôs day just behind us, some readers are asking if there have been any changes to policies related to office romance following the start of the #metoo movement. to be honest, i haven‚Äôt personally heard of or seen any particularly radical changes in the canadian market, but there certainly are reports of increased sensitivity to the issue. at the very least, organizations of all sorts are reviewing their human resource policies and reporting procedures, and are increasing awareness training for all employees in the area of sexual harassment and appropriate communication. the goal is to get ahead of any problems that might arise.part of the challenge that all organizations face is that although the laws on sexual harassment are very clear, a key issue ‚Äî if not the ‚Äúreal‚Äù issue ‚Äî is the organizational culture in which people work. in other words, will the culture allow sexual misbehaviour to be accepted or ignored and swept under the rug? or will the organizational culture simply encourage debate on interpretation and stall any effort to deal with misbehaviour?thus, one of the biggest and most positive results of the #metoo movement is that leaders are now focusing more effort on ensuring their‚Ä¶

‚Ä¢‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢‚Ä¢
our minds are a constant work of art, carefully collecting memories and feelings as we grow. like most, my mind has developed into a museum of my childhood, preserving each memory just in case i have to ever protect myself again. with that though comes tremendous upkeep, an exhaustion i can‚Äôt quite explain, and an immense sadness i feel every time i read or hear another #metoo experience, mostly because i know i‚Äôm not alone, yet i know i am alone.

text:
we spend so much time in our left brains that we miss out on our creativity.  tap into your creativity! be creative!  there is no one way to be creative - whether it is drawing, painting, writing, singing, baking or something else.  you don‚Äôt have to be good at it to express yourself (& you can‚Äôt get good at it if you never do it!) .
.

one thing i have noticed about myself is that now that i am not so stressed out, i see nature‚Äôs colors more and they are more vibrant than ever before. (mindfulness does work! üòä). i like to capture those colors with the pics i take (and usually share here!). .

take the time to tap into your creativity! you may be surprised about what you learn about yourself üíñ . üì∏: geordanna cordero-fields

text:
#sweetheartsaturday #blackhistorymonth spotlight on anita hill: attorney, civil rights educator, women's rights advocate and current university professor of social policy, law, and women's studies at brandeis university. hill became a national figure in 1991 when she accused her then employer and u.s. supreme court nominee clarence thomas of sexual harassment. despite the senate judiciary committee ruling against hill, and the disparaging doubt it strove to cast on hill‚Äôs testimony as well as her character for years to come, hill‚Äôs courage to come forward collectively increased complaints of sexual harassment in the workplace, positively affected federal policy change around it, and contributed to a larger number of women elected to congress in the following year. public opinion would finally sway in favor of anita hill.
.
hill‚Äôs trial came back into the spotlight most recently during the 2018 sexual assault testimony from dr. christine blasey ford against supreme court nominee brett kavanaugh, in which she publicly related her own experience and spoke out against the senate judiciary committee and in support of dr. ford: ‚Äúat the end of the day, i certainly believed her.‚Äù thank you, anita hill.
.
#anitahill #notagain #metoo #istillbelieveanitahill #drblaseyford #believesurvivors #believesurvivors #believesurvivors
